The paper deals with the computational complexity of equilibrium approximation problems, which is a topic in theoretical computer science. The use of generalized circuits is a common tool in this area, which suggests cs.CC (Computational Complexity) as the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses Boolean operations and gate types, which are topics in graph theory and discrete mathematics, suggesting cs.GT (Discrete Mathematics) as another likely sub-category. The paper also involves the study of algorithms and optimization, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper discusses technical issues and the need for simpler and more natural reductions, which could fall under cs.LG (Machine Learning).
